Rotating the original parabola 180 degrees changes its equation to $y=-(x-2)^2+3$. Shifting this last parabola to the left changes its equation to $y=-(x+1)^2+3$. Shifting it down changes its equation to $y=-(x+1)^2+1$. So the equation of $A'$ is $y=-(x+1)^2+1$. To find the zeros of this parabola, we set $y=0$ to get $0=-(x+1)^2+1$. Expanding the right hand side gives $0=-x^2-2x$. Dividing through by $-1$ and factoring out an $x$ from the right hand side, we get $0=x(x+2)$, so either $x=0$ or $x+2=0$. Thus, $a=0$ and $b=-2$, so $a+b=\boxed{-2}$.

We will need to know how much sand Sean has, so we need to find the volumes of each of the two cylindrical containers. If the height of each container is $h$, the old container holds $4^2h\pi = 16h\pi$ cubic centimeters of sand. The new container holds $8^2h\pi = 64h\pi$ cubic centimeters of sand. We can now find how many new containers Sean will need:  \begin{align*}
&12\text{ old containers}\cdot \frac{16h\pi\text{ cm}^3}{1\text{ old container}} \cdot \frac{1 \text{ new container}}{64h\pi\text{ cm}^3} \\
&\qquad = \boxed{3}\text{ new containers}.
\end{align*}

problem:
There are two different isosceles triangles whose side lengths are integers and whose areas are $120.$ One of these two triangles, $\triangle XYZ,$ is shown. Determine the perimeter of the second triangle.

